title.narrative: 4.1 INCREASED CAPACITY TO LEGISLATE, PLAN AND BUDGET FOR CHILDREN

description.narrative: 4.1 State institutions and other partners have increased capacity to legislate, plan and budget to prevent and respond to child protection concerns including during humanitarian situations, which contributes to Prevention And Response Services For Violence Against Children, Promotion Of Care, Mental Health And Psychosocial Well-Being And Justice, Protection From Violence, Exploitation, Abuse And Neglect, Protection From Violence, Exploitation, Abuse And Neglect (Covid). UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Public Engagement, Data, Research, Evaluation And Knowledge Management, Developing And Leveraging Resources And Partnerships, Evaluations, Research And Data, Fostering Innovation And Use Of New Technologies, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By 2022, children and adolescents have improved protection from all forms of violence, abuse and exploitation.

title.narrative: 4.1 State institutions and other partners have increased capacity to legislate, plan and budget to prevent and respond to childprotection concerns including during humanitarian situations

description.narrative: UNICEF continued engaging with (sub)national authorities to avoid de-prioritization of CP ;issues.Progress was registered in implementing non-custodial measures for children, strengthening of national case management practices, resource allocation to child protection services in more than 30 municipalities. Despite continued challenges to implement the Alternative Care procedures, pandemic-induced reintegration of children in institutions resulted in a historic 25% decrease of institutionalization, a milestone in support of care reform advocacy. UNICEF partnered with local governments and CSOs to adapt child protection policies to the federal system and enhance safe family—based care for more than ;;4450 children including in emergencies .; | Status:Partially met | As-of Date:04/01/2022
